This is the AmigaGuide® file CLChatGUI.guide, produced by Makeinfo-1.55 from 
the input file CLChatGUI.texi.


@Node Main "CLChatGUI.guide"



@{b}CLChatGUI@{ub}
*********

Welcome to the @{i}CLChatGUI@{ui}, a full-featured GUI client to the
@{i}CLChatSystem@{ui} for @{b}AmiTCP@{ub}.  The @{b}CLChatSystem@{ub}, which is originally
part of the @{i}Connectline@{ui} BBS package, provides a multoi-server, IRC-like
chat system with multiple channels, private messaging, operator
privileges and more.

Within @{b}Connectline@{ub}, also online user and @{b}Hydra@{ub} file transfer protocol
chat user may join the chat.  See the `CLChatServer Documentation' for
more information about @{b}Connectline@{ub}.


- Usage: -

 @{" Connecting " Link "Connecting"}        Connecting to a server
 @{" Using CLChatGUI " Link "Using CLChatGUI"}   Doing chat
 @{" Setup " Link "Setup"}             Setting preferences
 @{" FileTransfer " Link "FileTransfer"}      Transfering files directly
 @{" ARexx commands " Link "ARexx commands"}    ARexx commands

- other stuff: -

 @{" Server Commands " Link "Server Commands"}   List of standard server commands
 @{" ARCnet " Link "ARCnet"}            The Amiga Relay Chat Network
 @{" Copyright " Link "Copyright"}         Copyrights, author info and updates
 @{" History " Link "History"}           Revision history
 @{" Index " Link "Index"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Connecting" "CLChatGUI.guide/Connecting"
@Next "Using CLChatGUI"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Connecting
**********

Installation is fairly simply.  Simply put the archive contents
somewhere on your harddisk.  Note that you need @{b}MUI 2.3@{ub} or better!

Before you can use @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub}, you must connect to a chat server running
@{b}CLChatD@{ub}.

When started, @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} will prompt you for a server name and a port
number to connect to.

If you are connected to a LAN, you should ask your network adminstrator
for both server name and port number.

If you are connected to the Internet, see @{"ARCnet" Link "ARCnet"} for a good choice of
servers to connect to.

You must also specify a @{b}Nickname@{ub} and your @{b}Realname@{ub}.  The nickname is a
kind of username used within the chat system.  It may be up to 15 byte
long and must consist of letters, digits and the characters @{b}.@{ub} and @{b}_@{ub}.
The realname is used for informational purposes only.

Note that the server may reject your connection attempt because the
entered nickname is invalid or already in use by another chat user.
Change your nick and retry the connection.

CLChatGUI keeps a history of the last servers you have connected to.
You may choose from the history by clicking on the popup button right
from the server name string gadget.  The history is saved within the
configuration file.

Local chat
**********

If you start the client on a machine running the @{b}CLChatServer@{ub}, it will
not connect using AmiTCP, but directly link to the chat server to
reduce overhead.

If you want to avoid this behaviour, e.g. for testing purposes, start
@{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} with the @{b}TCPMode@{ub} keyword or specify the @{b}TCPMode@{ub} tooltype.


@EndNode

@Node "Using CLChatGUI" "CLChatGUI.guide/Using CLChatGUI"
@Next "Setup"
@Prev "Connecting"
@Toc "Main"

Using CLChatGUI
***************

After connecting to the chat server, the main window opens.  It
consists of a channel selection gadget, a topic gadget, the main output
window, your input string gadget and the user operation gadget group.
It also features a menu bar with several options and shortcuts for
server commands.

You send text to the chat server by simply entering it in the input
gadget.  Commands are also send to the server by entering them in the
input gadget.  You may want to use the @{b}/HELP@{ub} command to learn about
available server commands.  The input gadget is normally automatically
activated; if it is not, simply press @{b}SPACE@{ub} to activate it.  A history
of the last 100 lines entered is kept; you may use @{b}Cursor/UP@{ub} or
@{b}Cursor/DOWN@{ub} for accessing entries in the history.

Changing channels is done by entering a new channel name in the channel
selection gadget.  Note that the server will automatically create a
channel if it does not exist. Already existing channels may be selected
with the popup listview right of the channel gadget. The popup button
has a hidden keyboard shortcut @{b}h@{ub} which opens the channel selection
listview.

If you have channel operator status, you may change the current
channel's topic by entering a new one in the topic gadget.  The
contents of this gadget are automatically updated if someone else
changes the topic.

User operations
***************

The user listview displays all users currently logged into the chat
server and the name of the channel they are currently on. Users with
channel operator privilege are marked with a @{b} @@{ub}, users with chat
operator privilege are marked with a @{b}!@{ub} before the name.

Double clicking on an entry in the user listview requests a @{b}/WHOIS user@{ub}
command from the server.  Pressing the @{b}Dialog@{ub} button opens a special
so-called dialog window.  A dialog window works much like the main
windows, but every text entered within a dialog window is send directly
as a private message to the user.  Also, any incoming private messages
from this user are displayed in the dialog window and not the main
window.  If the @{b}Auto@{ub} checkbox is selected, a new dialog window is
created for the originator of every incoming private message.

If you have channel or chat operator privilege, you may also use the
@{b}OP@{ub}, @{b}DEOP@{ub} and @{b}KICK@{ub} buttons to perform the requested operation on
the selected user.

Via the @{b}PING@{ub} button you can request a PING request from the selected
user. If the user is running the GUI client, too, you will eventually
receive a reply stating the round-tripe time from you to the remote
user. This is usefull for TCP connections only.

If you have a TCP connection, you may also use the @{b}Send Files@{ub} option to
directly send files to the remote user; see @{"FileTransfer" Link "FileTransfer"} for more
information about this operation.

Setting the @{b}AWAY@{ub} checkmark causes the AWAY message to be printed, and
every private message to you will automatically respond with @{b}Nick is
away (AWAY message)@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "Setup" "CLChatGUI.guide/Setup"
@Next "FileTransfer"
@Prev "Using CLChatGUI"
@Toc "Main"

Setup
*****

In the setup window, you may modify several operation attributes.

@{b}Autoconnect@{ub} will cause an automatic connection attempt each time the
@{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} is started. Setting @{b}Auto Reconnect@{ub} will cause automatic
reconnect attempts if the connections drops.

@{b}File Receive Path@{ub} specifies the path you want incoming CLFT files to
go (See @{"FileTransfer" Link "FileTransfer"}.). Setting @{b}Auto Receive@{ub} will start a CLFT receive
session without prompting you for confirmation.

@{b}Max. Number of Lines@{ub} specifies how many lines of incoming text will be
stored for the output listview.

You may log all or some of the chat server output to a log file; you may
individually select @{b}Private@{ub}, @{b}Server@{ub} or normal @{b}Text@{ub} messages to be
stored in the log file.

The @{b}Event Handling@{ub} checkboxes set the reaction of special events.  You
may set @{b}Deiconify@{ub} to automatically deiconify the application on the
given event, and @{b}DisplayBeep@{ub} to just have the screen beep.

The message section allows you to specify standard texts send to the
chat for given operations. The @{b}AWAY@{ub} message is set when you select the
@{b}AWAY@{ub} checkbox in the main window, the @{b}BACK@{ub} message is send when you
clear the checkbox. The @{b}KICK@{ub} message is a default kick reason if you
kick users using the @{b}KICK@{ub} button below the user listview.

You may create several different configuration files using the @{b}Save...@{ub}
and @{b}Load...@{ub} items from the menu bar.  If you create icons for the
configurations, you can start @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} by simply doubly clicking on
the configuration icon.


@EndNode

@Node "FileTransfer" "CLChatGUI.guide/FileTransfer"
@Next "ARexx commands"
@Prev "Setup"
@Toc "Main"

FileTransfer
************

If you connect via AmiTCP, you may also use the @{i}CLFT@{ui} protocol to
directly send files to users linked to the chat network (comparable to
the IRC `DCC protocol').  Simply select the user you want to send to,
press the @{b}Send files@{ub} button and a filerequester will open. You can also
directly drop Workbench icons onto the user listview to have the
correspondending files to be send to the currently selected user. If
you have dialog windows open, you may also directly send files by
dropping Workbench icons onto the dialog window.

When you have selected files, a @{b}CLFT@{ub} request will be send to the
remote user, and the @{b}CLFT@{ub} sender window will open on your side,
awaiting a connect from the receiving site.  The receiver will then
eventually connect to you via TCP and grab the files offered to him.

If you receive incoming @{b}CLFT@{ub} requests, a requester will open showing
you the originator of the request, the number of files to be send and a
list of the files to be transfered.  You may accept or reject the
request, or you may change to destination directory.  Use the
@{"Setup" Link "Setup"} window to change the default path in which incoming files are
stored.  If you have @{b}Auto Receive@{ub} set, no prompt will appear, but
receiving will start immediately.

Incoming files are tagged with a filenote designating the originator
nick and IP address for later identification.  If an equally named file
already exists, the file name is postpended with ".2", ".3" etc.

You may abort file transfers at any time by clicking on the close
gadget of the receive or send window.  All transfers currently waiting
or in progress will automatically terminate if you quite @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub}.
Note that you cannot send files to users which are connected via TelNet
or the Connectline ANSI client.


@EndNode

@Node "ARexx commands" "CLChatGUI.guide/ARexx commands"
@Next "Server Commands"
@Prev "FileTransfer"
@Toc "Main"

ARexx commands
**************

@{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} features an ARexx port. The port name is @{b}CLCHATCLIENT.nr@{ub},
with @{b}nr@{ub} starting at 1 and increasing for every instance of the program
started.

Besides the builtin MUI commands (see the `MUI User Guide'), @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub}
current features two commands:

@{b}SEND TEXT/F@{ub}
     Sends the given text string as it was entered in the input string
     gadget.  Note that you may also send server commands this way.

@{b}RECONNECT@{ub}
     Cause the @{b}CLChatGUI@{ub} to reconnect to the current server.


@EndNode

@Node "Server Commands" "CLChatGUI.guide/Server Commands"
@Next "ARCnet"
@Prev "ARexx commands"
@Toc "Main"

Server Commands
***************

Below is a list of normally available server commands. Don't forget to
use the @{b}/HELP@{ub} command to learn if your server supports a different
command set.

   @{b}*@{ub} /CHANNEL [name]
     Join or create a channel

   @{b}*@{ub} /INFO [name]
     Show all or specific channel

   @{b}*@{ub} /WHO
     List users in channel

   @{b}*@{ub} /USERS
     List all users in chat. Note that the output from this command is
     silently interpreted by the client and not displayed in the output
     window.

   @{b}*@{ub} /USERS S
     List all users in chat together with the servers they are on

   @{b}*@{ub} /WHOIS nick
     Show info about user

   @{b}*@{ub} /MSG nick msg
     Send private msg to nick

   @{b}*@{ub} /NICK [nick]
     View or change your nick

   @{b}*@{ub} /ME msg
     Send action string

   @{b}*@{ub} /VERSION
     Show server version

   @{b}*@{ub} /SERVERS
     Show other servers connected to your local server

@{i}Operator only commands:@{ui}

   @{b}*@{ub} /OP nick
     Give operator state to nick

   @{b}*@{ub} /DEOP nick
     Remove operator state from nick

   @{b}*@{ub} /TOPIC topic
     Set topic of channel

   @{b}*@{ub} /KICK nick reason
     Kick nick out of channel

There are also special @{i}Chat operator commands@{ui} which are not visible to
the normal user or channel operator.  Use the @{b}/HELP@{ub} command to obtain
a list of chat operator commands directly from the server.


@EndNode

@Node "ARCnet" "CLChatGUI.guide/ARCnet"
@Next "Copyright"
@Prev "Server Commands"
@Toc "Main"

ARCnet
******

@{i}ARCnet@{ui}, the @{i}Amiga Relay Chat Network@{ui}, is a Internet based network of
@{b}CLChatServers@{ub} available for public usage. As the time of writing, the
following servers were connected to the network:

   @{b}*@{ub} us1.clchat.vapor.com

   @{b}*@{ub} us2.clchat.vapor.com

   @{b}*@{ub} us3.clchat.vapor.com

   @{b}*@{ub} us4.clchat.vapor.com

   @{b}*@{ub} de.clchat.vapor.com

   @{b}*@{ub} it.clchat.vapor.com

All servers run the @{b}CLChatServer@{ub} on port 5555. All these servers are
online 24h/day.

Check out @{b}http://monet.nfinity.com/arcnet/@{ub} for up-to-date information
about the ArcNet server list.


@EndNode

